alist and figurative traditions seemed to occur. Wolff concludes by considering this re-emergence, as well as the limitations of earlier discussions of the struggles of realist and figurative art to endure the currents of modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnicity in art. 0aGender identity in art. 0aModernism (Art)zGreat Britain. 0aModernism (Art)zUnited States. 0aPainting, Americany20th century. 0aPainting, Britishy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aArt History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171746840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717468/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles